namedPeople.description: Rohit (Devanagri: रोहित), [ˈroːɦɪt̪]) is a given name, typically male, used among Indian people. It is also used in some parts of Nepal. It is mostly used by Jains, Hindus, and Sikhs. The word "rohit" signifies the color red. It is derived from Sanskrit, meaning "the first rays of the sun". The early morning sunlight usually has a reddish tint. It is also said to be derived from the Sanskrit word Rohitah (रोहित:) which signifies a red coloured deer – a form which Brahma once took. [ˈɽoːɦɪtɐ].

transcript.text: Hello, welcome to the Onprint shop.
In today's video, we're going to walk through the process of generating short links for your products and sharing them effectively.
First of all, let's talk about why you might want to create short links.
Long UR LS can be cumbersome, especially when sharing on social media, in emails, or even through text messages.
Whereas a short link not only looks cleaner but can also be tracked for analytics purposes.
So let's see how you can create short links and use them for shopping feeds and link sharing.
In the admin panel, navigate to the SEO section.
Click on the site Maps.
As you can identify, the screen has been revamped, and Google Feeds and Facebook feeds are moved to separate tabs.
Now one new tab, Product Feed Variance, has been introduced.
The Product Feed Variance tab will allow you to create product variance by combining selected sizes, quantities, and options.
Let's start by adding product variants.
Click on the Add button from the top of the screen.
On the next screen, select the product for which you want to create variants and then short links.
We are selecting standard business cards.
In the next step, choose the size, quantity, and options for creating combinations and then click on the Continue button.
In the final step, you can preview feed links and title of the combinations to activate the links.
You have these check boxes against each variant.
If you want to generate links with the inactive state, you can simply uncheck the box and then click on the save button from top of the screen.
All the variants will be listed on the product feed variance listing page.
You will have the option to view links to all the variants, edit the combinations or delete the variant if it is not required.
You can even import these variants with the import feature.
The next step after creating variants is how you share these with your people.

Moving to the Google Feeds tab, you can select the fields as previously and then select the product by including some products, excluding some, or generating feeds for all out of the products selected in the list.

The products with variance will have feed generated for each variant, and the product without any variant will have feed generated for the base product with base pricing and default options considered.
Now click on the Generate button to start generating the feeds.
One download feed button will be available to download the generated feeds in XML format that you can use to showcase the products in Google search engine.
You can similarly generate feeds for the Facebook platform.
In addition, you can manually create product feed variance one by one from the price calculator.
You can select the size, quantity and options in calculator and click on the Share product link to generate the feed.
Simply click on the Save to Feed button in the front store.
Your customers will also have the option to share the product combinations they have selected using the Share Product link.
They can copy the link and share the product configurations or even send or receive the same link via e-mail or download the estimation in PDF format.
The display of the Send estimation block depends on the setting from the site settings.
That's it.
This is how you can generate short links for shopping feeds or share product combinations.
If you have any questions, our support executives are here to help.
Just reach out through live chat on on printshop.com.
Thanks for tuning in.

metadata about each URL (when it was last updated,how often it usually changes, and how important it is, relative to other URLs in the site) so that search engines can more intelligently crawl
